# Markdown Rules — ElliottSecurity KnowledgeOS

## Formatting
- One H1 per file; H1 must match `title` frontmatter.
- Use ATX headings (`##`, `###`); never skip levels.
- Prefer short paragraphs, lists, and tables over walls of text.
- Use fenced code blocks with language tags.
- Use Obsidian callouts for summary/warning/todo signals.

## Writing Style
- Enterprise SOC tone: precise, operational, non-hype.
- Prefer actionable language ("Do X when Y") over vague advice.
- Mark unknowns with TODOs; never invent facts.

## Folder Conventions
- KnowledgeOS lives under `knowledgeos/`.
- Numbered domain roots are stable; do not rename casually.
- Never leave empty folders — include README + Overview + starter notes.

## Naming
- Note titles: `Title Case With Spaces.md`
- Folders: `NN-Title-Case-With-Hyphens`
- IDs: `ES-DET-####`, `ES-HUNT-####`, `ES-IR-YYYY-####`

## Linking
- Primary links: `[[Note Title]]`
- Every durable note needs a **Related Notes** section.
- Update domain Overview when adding major notes.

## Metadata
```yaml
---
title: "Example"
tags: [domain, topic]
status: draft | active | canonical | archived
type: note
created: YYYY-MM-DD
updated: YYYY-MM-DD
---
```

## Templates
- Prefer templates from `knowledgeos/22-Templates/`.
- Align with [[STANDARDS]] and [[PROJECT_CONTEXT]].

## Documentation Standards
- Answer: what / why / how / dependencies / risks.
- No secrets in Git.
- Mermaid for diagrams where helpful.
